window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2022>1>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2022","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"EQUILIBRIUM OF FORCES : CONDITIONS FOR EQUILIBRIUM OF RIGID BODIES UNDER THE ACTION OF PARALLEL AND NON-PARALLEL FORCES","question":"You are provided with a metre rule, a weight hanger, slotted masses, M, a piece of string, a weighing balance and a knife edge.     Use the diagram above as a guide to perform the experiment.    (i) Using the weighing balance, determine and record the mass, Mo, of the unloaded metre rule.    (ii) Determine and record the mass, M, of the weight hanger.    (ii) Suspend the metre rule horizontally on the knife edge. Adjust the knife edge to a point G on the metre rule where it balances horizontally.    (iv) Record the distance, d = AG.    (v) Suspend the weight hanger securely at a point, P, on the metre rule such that AP = 5 cm. Keep the hanger at this point throughout the experiment    (vi) Add a mass, M = 20 g to the hanger, adjust the knife edge to a point K on the metre rule such that it balances horizontally as shown in the diagram above.    (vii) Determine and record the distance z = AK.    (vii) Record M and evaluate y = (z - 5), x = (d - z) and v = xy\\frac{x}{y}yx\u200b    (ix) Repeat the experiment for M = 40 g, 60 g, 80 g and 100 g. In each case, evaluate y, x and v.    (x) Tabulate the results.    (xi) Plot a graph with M on the vertical axis and v on the horizontal axis, starting both axes from the origin (0,0).    (xii) Determine the slope, s, of the graph.    (xiii) Determine the intercept, c, on the vertical axis.    (xiv) State two precautions taken to ensure accurate results.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Mo = 117 g, M = 31.5 g, d = 50.0cm    S/NM(g)z(cm)y(cm)x(cm)v12036.431.413.60.43324032.927.917.10.61336030.325.319.70.77948028.223.221.80.940510026.321.323.71.113        (xii) s = \u25b3M\u25b3v\\frac{\u25b3M}{\u25b3v}\u25b3v\u25b3M\u200b = M2\u2212M1v2\u2212v1\\frac{M_{2}-M_{1}}{v_{2}-v_{1}}v2\u200b\u2212v1\u200bM2\u200b\u2212M1\u200b\u200b = 87.5\u221222.51\u22120.45\\frac{87.5-22.5}{1-0.45}1\u22120.4587.5\u221222.5\u200b = 650.55\\frac{65}{0.55}0.5565\u200b = 118.18 g    (xiii) To get the equation of the line (y = mx + c):    y - 20 = 118.18(x - 0.433)    y - 20 = 118.18x - 51.17    y = 118.18x - 31.17    \u2234 c = -31.17 g    (xiv) Precautions:    1. I switched off fans and closed windows to eliminate draughts that could disrupt the balancing.    2. I ensured the weight hanger and slotted masses were securely attached to prevent sudden falls.    3. I avoided parallax errors when taking readings of distances on the metre rule.    4. I confirmed that the mass on the hanger did not touch or rest against the table or other objects.    5. I took repeated readings for consistency and improved accuracy.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2022>1>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2022","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"EQUILIBRIUM OF FORCES : CONDITIONS FOR EQUILIBRIUM OF RIGID BODIES UNDER THE ACTION OF PARALLEL AND NON-PARALLEL FORCES","question":"Under what condition is an object said to be in a stable equilibrium?","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"An object is said to be in stable equilibrium if, when slightly displaced, it tends to return to its original position. This happens under the condition that the center of gravity of the object is raised during the displacement and subsequently returns to the lowest possible position when the displacement force is removed. In this state, any small tilt or movement creates a restoring force or moment that counters the displacement.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2022>1>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2022","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"EQUILIBRIUM OF FORCES : PRINCIPLE OF MOMENTS","question":"A uniform beam of weight 50 N has a body of weight 100 N hung at one end of it. If the beam is 12 m long, determine the distance of a support from a 100 N body for it to balance horizontally.    (Provide your answer with the unit e.g 123 J)","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Let the distance = y,        100y = 50(6 - y)    100y = 300 - 50y    150y = 300    y = 2 m","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2022>2>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2022","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"FLUID AT REST : EQUILIBRIUM OF BODIES: LAW OF FLOTATION~~HEAT ENERGY : EVAPORATION AND BOILING","question":"You are provided with a loaded boiling tube with a centimeter scale fixed inside it, a transparent vessel filled with water, standard masses 2 g, 5g and 10 g, and a slide vernier caliper.     Use the diagram above as a guide to perform the experiment.    (i) Use the slide vernier caliper to measure and record the external diameter, D, of the boiling tube.    (ii) Evaluated A = 0.25\u03c0D2, where \u03c0 = 3.14    (iii) Place the loaded boiling tube gently in the water in the transparent vessel such that it floats vertically.    (iv) Read and record the depth of immersion, y, from the zero mark of the scale fixed inside, the boiling tube.    (v) Add a mass, m = 2 g, to the boiling tube. Read and record the new depth of immersion, y, from the zero mark of the scale.    (vi) Evaluate h = (y - yo), log h and log m.    (vii) Repeat the experiment for four other values of m = 5 g, 7 g, 10 g, and 12 g. In each case, record y and evaluate h, log h, and log m.    (viii) Tabulate the results.    (ix) Plot a graph with log m on the vertical axis and log h on the horizontal axis starting both axes from the origin (0,0).    (x) Determine the slope, s of the graph    (xi) Determine the intercept, c on the vertical axis    (xii) Given that log (AP) = c, calculate P    (xiii) State two precautions taken to ensure accurate results.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"D = 2.50 cm, A = 0.25\u03c0D2 = 0.25 \u00d7 3.14 \u00d7 2.52 = 4.91 cm2    S/Nm(g)y(cm)h(cm)log hlog m1211.60.6-0.2220.3012512.01.00.0000.6993712.41.40.1460.84541013.02.00.3011.00051213.42.40.3801.079        (x) s = \u25b3log\u2061(m)\u25b3log\u2061(h)\\frac{\u25b3\\log{\\left(m\\right)}}{\u25b3\\log{\\left(h\\right)}}\u25b3log(h)\u25b3log(m)\u200b = log\u2061(m)2\u2212log\u2061(m)1log\u2061(h)2\u2212log\u2061(h)1\\frac{\\log{\\left(m\\right)}_{2}-\\log{\\left(m\\right)}_{1}}{\\log{\\left(h\\right)}_{2}-\\log{\\left(h\\right)}_{1}}log(h)2\u200b\u2212log(h)1\u200blog(m)2\u200b\u2212log(m)1\u200b\u200b = 0.975\u22120.4750.275\u2212\u22120.125\\frac{0.975-0.475}{0.275--0.125}0.275\u2212\u22120.1250.975\u22120.475\u200b = 0.50.4\\frac{0.5}{0.4}0.40.5\u200b = 1.25    (xi) c = 0.64    (xii) log (AP) = c    log (4.91 \u00d7 P) = 0.64    4.91P = 100.64    4.91P = 4.37    P = 4.374.91\\frac{4.37}{4.91}4.914.37\u200b = 0.89 cm-2    (xiii) Precautions:    1. I gently lowered the boiling tube into the transparent vessel to prevent splashing or tilting.    2. I ensured the boiling tube was floating vertically and stable throughout the experiment.    3. I avoided parallax error while reading the depth of immersion on the scale inside the boiling tube.    4. I ensured the scale was clearly visible and properly aligned for accurate readings.    5. I avoided overloading the boiling tube to prevent submersion or tilting.    6. I verified the accuracy of the slide vernier caliper by checking for zero error before measuring.    7. I ensured the water level in the vessel was sufficient for the boiling tube to float freely without touching the bottom.    8. I handled all equipment carefully to avoid accidental spills or misalignment.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2022>2>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2022","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"FLUID AT REST : EQUILIBRIUM OF BODIES: LAW OF FLOTATION","question":"State in full the law on which the experiment in (a) is based.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"The experiment is based on The Law of Flotation, which states:    \"A floating body displaces its own weight of the fluid in which it floats.\"    This law explains how the depth of immersion of the loaded boiling tube adjusts to ensure that the weight of the tube and its contents is balanced by the upthrust exerted by the displaced water.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2022>2>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2022","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"FLUID AT REST : EQUILIBRIUM OF BODIES: ARCHIMEDES\u2019 PRINCIPLE","question":"A uniform cylindrical rod is 0.63 m long and it has a cross-sectional area of 0.1 m2. Calculate the depth of immersion of the rod if it floats vertically in a liquid of relative density 1.26. [density of rod = 720 kgm\u22123, g = 10 ms\u22122].    (Provide your answer with the unit e.g 123.123 J)","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"To determine the depth of immersion of the rod, we use the principle of flotation:    Weight of the rod = Weight of the liquid displaced.    Step 1: Weight of the rod    The weight of the rod is given by:    Weight of the rod = Volume of the rod \u00d7 Density of the rod \u00d7 g.    The volume of the rod is:    Vrod \u200b= Cross-sectional area \u00d7 Length.    Substitute the given values:    Vrod \u200b= 0.1 m2 \u00d7 0.63 m = 0.063 m3.    The weight of the rod becomes:    Weight of the rod = 0.063 m3 \u00d7 720 kgm-3 \u00d7 10 ms-2.    Step 2: Weight of the liquid displaced    The weight of the liquid displaced is:    Weight of liquid displaced = Volume of immersion \u00d7 Density of liquid \u00d7 g.    The density of the liquid is:    Density of liquid = Relative density of liquid \u00d7 Density of water = 1.26 \u00d7 1000 kgm-3 =  1260 kgm-3.    The volume of immersion (Vimmersion\u200b) is:    Vimmersion\u200b = Cross-sectional area \u00d7 Depth of immersion.    Step 3: Equating the weights    Equate the weight of the rod and the weight of the liquid displaced:    063 \u00d7 720 \u00d7 10 = 0.1 \u00d7 d \u00d7 1260 \u00d7 10.    Simplify to solve for d (depth of immersion):    d=0.063 \u00d7 7200.1 \u00d7 1260=0.36","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2022>3>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2022","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : ELECTRIC CURRENT, POTENTIAL DIFFERENCE, RESISTANCE, E.M.F. AND INTERNAL RESISTANCE","question":"You are provided with a battery of e.m.f, E, a standard resistor, R, of resistance 2 \u03a9, a key, K, an ammeter, A, a jockey, J, a potentiometer, UV, and some connecting wires.    (i) Measure and record the emf, E, of the battery.    (ii) Set up the circuit as shown in the diagram above with the key open.    (iii) Place the jockey at the point, U, of the potentiometer wire. Close the key and record the reading, I, of the ammeter.    (iv) Place the jockey at a point T on the potentiometer wire UV such that d = UT = 30.0 cm.    (v) Close the circuit, read and record the current, I, on the ammeter,    (vi) Evaluate I-1.    (vi) Repeat the experiment for four other values of d = 40.0 cm, 50.0 cm, 60.0 cm and 70.0 cm. In each case, record I and evaluate I-1.    (vii) Tabulate the results    (ix) Plot a graph with d on the vertical axis and I-1 on the horizontal axis starting both axes from the origin (0,0).    (x) Determine the slope, s, of the graph.    (xi) From the graph determine the value Io of I when d = 0.     (xii) Given that E\u03b4\\frac{E}{\u03b4}\u03b4E\u200b = s, calculate \u03b4.    (xiii) State two precautions taken to ensure accurate results.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"E = 3.0 V, I = 0.72 A    S/Nd(cm)I(A)I-1(A-1)130.00.492.041240.00.442.273350.00.422.381460.00.392.564570.00.362.778        (x) s = \u25b3d\u25b3I\u22121\\frac{\u25b3d}{\u25b3I^{-1}}\u25b3I\u22121\u25b3d\u200b = d2\u2212d1I2\u22121\u2212I1\u22121\\frac{d_{2}-d_{1}}{I^{-1}_{2}-I^{-1}_{1}}I2\u22121\u200b\u2212I1\u22121\u200bd2\u200b\u2212d1\u200b\u200b = 62.5\u2212352.625\u22122.125\\frac{62.5-35}{2.625-2.125}2.625\u22122.12562.5\u221235\u200b = 27.50.5\\frac{27.5}{0.5}0.527.5\u200b = 55 cmA    (xi) When d = 0, I-1 = 1.5 A-1. \u2234 I = 11.5\\frac{1}{1.5}1.51\u200b = 0.67 A    (xii) E\u03b4\\frac{E}{\u03b4}\u03b4E\u200b = s    3\u03b4\\frac{3}{\u03b4}\u03b43\u200b = 55    3 = 55\u03b4    \u03b4 = 355\\frac{3}{55}553\u200b = 0.055 Vcm-1A-1    (xiii) Precautions:    1. I ensured all connections were tight to minimize resistance and ensure accurate readings.    2. I avoided parallax errors when reading both the metre rule and the ammeter.    3. I ensured the potentiometer wire was clean and free of kinks or irregularities for smooth operation.    4. I opened the key when not taking measurements to prevent unnecessary current flow and overheating of components.    5. I verified the absence of zero error in the ammeter before taking readings.    6. I avoided placing the jockey on the potentiometer wire for extended periods to prevent overheating or damage to the wire.    7. I repeated measurements to ensure consistency and accuracy of results.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2022>3>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2022","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : RESISTIVITY AND CONDUCTIVITY","question":"Write down the equation that connects the resistance, R, of a wire and the factors on which it depends. State the meaning of each of the symbols.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"The equation connecting the resistance R of a wire and the factors on which it depends is:    R = \u03c1LA\\frac{\u03c1L}{A}A\u03c1L\u200b \u200b    Meaning of the symbols:  R: Resistance of the wire, measured in ohms (\u03a9).  \u03c1: Resistivity of the material, measured in ohm-meters (\u03a9\u22c5m).  L: Length of the wire, measured in meters (m).  A: Cross-sectional area of the wire, measured in square meters (m2).  This formula shows that the resistance of a wire is directly proportional to its length and resistivity, and inversely proportional to its cross-sectional area.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2022>3>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2022","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : ELECTRIC ENERGY AND POWER","question":"An electric fan draws a current of 0.75 A in a 240 V circuit. Calculate the cost of using, the fan for 10 hours if the utility rate is $0.50 per kWh.    (Provide your answer without the dollar sign ($) and to 2 d.p)","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"P = IV    Power, P = 240\u00d70.751000\\frac{240\u00d70.75}{1000}1000240\u00d70.75\u200b = 0.18 kW    Energy consumed in 10hr = Pt =  0.18 \u00d7 10    = 1.8 kWh    Cost of energy = 1.8 \u00d7 0.5 = $0.90","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"}];